Scala is just as much a functional language as it is object-oriented, and the whole of functional programming rests on one deceptively simple idea: a function is a value. Not a special construct, not something you can only declare and call, but an ordinary value, like a number or a string. Once you truly accept that, everything else follows.

Look at the picture. You have some data, a list of integers called nums. And you have a function, f, whose type is Int to Int. You hand both of them to map. Notice that the function went in exactly the same way the data did, as an argument. The function is being passed around like any other value. That is the entire premise. Hold onto it as we go.

First, lambdas. A lambda is just a function written inline, without giving it a name first. Write val inc equals, open paren x colon Int close paren, arrow, x plus one. The arrow is what makes it a function literal. To the left of the arrow are the parameters; to the right is the body. And because a function is a value, it has a type, just like everything else. The type of inc is Int to Int, written Int, arrow, Int. You can even write that type out explicitly: val f colon Int to Int equals inc. You call a lambda exactly like any function: inc of ten gives you eleven.

Scala also gives you a lovely shorthand. When you write List of one, two, three, dot map, of underscore plus one, that underscore is a placeholder for the argument. Underscore plus one is just a terser way of writing x arrow x plus one. You will see that underscore everywhere in idiomatic Scala.

Second, higher-order functions. A higher-order function is simply a function that takes another function as a parameter, or returns one as a result, or both. Because functions are values, this requires no special machinery at all. Consider def twice, which takes a function f of type Int to Int, and a value x, and returns f of f of x. You are passing a function in. So twice of, underscore plus three, applied to ten, runs the increment-by-three twice and gives you sixteen.

Returning a function is just as natural. Def adder takes an Int n and returns an Int to Int. Its body is x arrow x plus n. So adder does not add anything itself; it builds and hands back a brand-new function that will add n. Call adder of five, and you get a function; name it add five. And because these are all just values, you can glue them together. Add five andThen, underscore times two, produces a single new function that first adds five, then doubles. Feed it one hundred, and you get two hundred and ten. That is function composition, and it is the heart of how functional programs are assembled: small functions combined into bigger ones.

Third, closures. Look again at adder. The function it returned, x arrow x plus n, used n. But n was a parameter of adder, which has already finished running by the time you call the returned function. So how does n survive? The returned function closed over it. A closure is a function that captures variables from the scope where it was created, and keeps them alive for as long as the function lives.

The counter example makes this vivid. Def counter declares a local var n set to zero, and returns a little lambda that increments n and yields it. Each time you call the returned function, n goes up: one, then two, then three. The variable n lives entirely inside counter, yet it persists between calls, because the closure is holding onto it. That captured state is the closure's private memory.

So there is the spine of functional Scala. Functions are values, which lets you write them inline as lambdas, pass and return and compose them as higher-order functions, and capture their surroundings as closures. And one habit ties it all together: favor pure functions, ones that only map inputs to outputs with no hidden side effects, and favor immutable data. Pure functions over immutable values are easy to compose, easy to test, and easy to reason about, and composing small honest functions is exactly what functional programming is.
